25|$|By {{the end of}} the Second World War, the United Kingdom owed Argentina m$n 2 billion {{after the}} country had filled the gaps in food {{shortages}} during the war effort. Following what was then a worldwide trend, the private companies were nationalised by the government of Juan Perón, beginning in 1946 with the French railways and then purchasing the British railways after an agreement was signed cancelling the British debt in 1947. Perón later claimed in an interview that the British envoys had offered him a bribe of US$100 million if the state paid an extra m$n 6 billion for the railways on top of the <b>debt</b> <b>cancellation.</b>|$|E
