50|$|Pittman then {{served as}} Deputy Assistant Secretary for International Development Finance and Debt at the Department of the Treasury, https://web.archive.org/web/20060115194806/http://www.treas.gov/organization/bios/pittman-e.html {{where he was}} a key {{architect}} and the lead U.S. negotiator of the 100 percent debt relief proposal endorsed by the G8 at the Gleneagles Summit in July 2005. http://commdocs.house.gov/committees/intlrel/hfa22265.000/hfa22265_0f.htm To date, this effort has delivered more than $40 billion in <b>debt</b> stock <b>cancellation</b> for the world’s poorest countries. He also acted as lead representative of the U.S. government for the multi-billion dollar replenishment negotiations of the World Bank, African Development Bank and Asian Development Bank in 2004-2005.|$|R
